1
00:00:37,970 --> 00:00:39,961
and I'll tell you what, the
storm system's still moving west.

2
00:00:40,072 --> 00:00:43,064
What are you looking at, Caroline?

3
00:00:44,109 --> 00:00:45,667
The wind, Mom.

4
00:00:48,781 --> 00:00:51,181
They say the hurricane is coming.

5
00:00:52,851 --> 00:00:56,014
I'm on a boat.

6
00:00:56,121 --> 00:00:58,385
I'm drifting.

7
00:01:00,726 --> 00:01:03,024
Can I do anything for you, Mom?

8
00:01:04,396 --> 00:01:06,261
Make anything easier?

9
00:01:07,232 --> 00:01:08,631
Oh, sugar...

10
00:01:09,168 --> 00:01:11,432
There's nothing left to do.

11
00:01:11,937 --> 00:01:13,529
Is what it is.

12
00:01:15,040 --> 00:01:18,009
Finding it harder to keep my eyes open.

13
00:01:19,978 --> 00:01:23,106
My mouth's full of cotton.

14
00:01:23,649 --> 00:01:25,776
There, there, Miss Daisy.

15
00:01:25,884 --> 00:01:28,614
You gonna scratch yourself to ribbons.

16
00:01:33,525 --> 00:01:36,323
Do you want any more medication, Mother?

17
00:01:37,229 --> 00:01:40,426
Doctor said you could have as much as you want.

18
00:01:40,532 --> 00:01:42,796
No need for anybody to suffer.

19
00:01:57,783 --> 00:02:00,684
A friend told me that she never had the chance

20
00:02:00,786 --> 00:02:03,084
to say goodbye to her mother.

21
00:02:06,225 --> 00:02:08,557
- I wanted to...
- It's okay.

22
00:02:08,660 --> 00:02:12,187
I wanted to tell you how much I'm gonna miss you so...

23
00:02:12,664 --> 00:02:13,756
Mom.

24
00:02:15,767 --> 00:02:17,530
Oh, Caroline.

25
00:02:23,342 --> 00:02:24,832
Are you afraid?

26
00:02:24,943 --> 00:02:26,638
I'm curious.

27
00:02:28,413 --> 00:02:30,040
What comes next?

28
00:02:35,587 --> 00:02:40,354
They built the train station in 1918.

29
00:02:41,393 --> 00:02:44,123
My father was there the day it opened.

30
00:02:45,797 --> 00:02:48,493
He said they had

31
00:02:50,435 --> 00:02:51,732
a tuba band playing.

32
00:02:56,508 --> 00:03:00,569
They had the finest clockmaker in all of the South

33
00:03:01,180 --> 00:03:03,978
to build that glorious clock.

34
00:03:05,851 --> 00:03:07,409
His name was...

35
00:03:09,321 --> 00:03:11,118
Mr. Gateau.

36
00:03:15,494 --> 00:03:16,654
Mr. Cake.

37
00:03:19,231 --> 00:03:23,395
He was married to a Creole of Evangeline Parish

38
00:03:23,502 --> 00:03:25,732
and they had a son.

39
00:03:27,673 --> 00:03:32,770
Mr. Gateau was, from birth, absolutely blind.

40
00:03:35,047 --> 00:03:39,279
When their son was old enough, he joined the army.

41
00:03:40,219 --> 00:03:44,588
And they prayed God would keep him out of harm's way.

42
00:03:47,526 --> 00:03:52,259
For months, he did nothing but work on that clock.

43
00:03:56,335 --> 00:03:57,768
One day,

44
00:03:59,137 --> 00:04:01,037
a letter came.

45
00:04:06,278 --> 00:04:10,009
And Mr. Gateau, done for the night,

46
00:04:10,716 --> 00:04:13,207
went up, alone, to bed.

47
00:04:15,887 --> 00:04:18,685
And their son came home.

48
00:04:23,862 --> 00:04:26,660
They buried him in the family plot,

49
00:04:26,765 --> 00:04:30,667
where he would be with them when their time came.

50
00:04:32,671 --> 00:04:35,765
Mr. Cake worked on his clock,

51
00:04:38,644 --> 00:04:42,239
laboring to finish.

52
00:04:44,149 --> 00:04:47,482
It was a morning to remember.

53
00:04:48,787 --> 00:04:51,915
Papa said there were people everywhere.

54
00:04:53,358 --> 00:04:55,918
Even Teddy Roosevelt came.

55
00:05:13,679 --> 00:05:15,544
It's running backwards!

56
00:05:17,182 --> 00:05:18,911
I made it that way

57
00:05:20,519 --> 00:05:22,384
so that perhaps the boys that we lost in the war

58
00:05:22,487 --> 00:05:23,852
might stand and come home again.

59
00:05:28,760 --> 00:05:30,193
Home to farm,

60
00:05:31,296 --> 00:05:32,490
work,

61
00:05:34,066 --> 00:05:35,761
have children.

62
00:05:39,071 --> 00:05:41,539
To live long, full lives.

63
00:05:44,710 --> 00:05:47,406
Perhaps my own son might come home again.

64
00:05:56,088 --> 00:05:58,613
I'm sorry if I've offended anybody.

65
00:06:00,192 --> 00:06:02,456
I hope you enjoy my clock.

66
00:06:03,362 --> 00:06:07,230
Mr. Cake was never seen again.

67
00:06:11,603 --> 00:06:16,006
Some say he died of a broken heart.

68
00:06:17,776 --> 00:06:20,040
Some say he went to sea.

69
00:06:25,183 --> 00:06:26,343
Excuse me.

70
00:06:26,451 --> 00:06:29,011
Do you mind if I make a call?
Somebody's watching my little boy.

71
00:06:29,121 --> 00:06:30,349
Sure.

72
00:06:40,599 --> 00:06:42,829
I hope I haven't disappointed you.

73
00:06:42,934 --> 00:06:46,028
You couldn't disappoint me.

74
00:06:47,506 --> 00:06:52,375
Well, I know I don't have much to show for myself.

75
00:06:54,946 --> 00:06:57,380
Find my dark suitcase.

76
00:07:01,753 --> 00:07:04,654
There's a diary.

77
00:07:06,825 --> 00:07:07,883
This?

78
00:07:10,629 --> 00:07:13,530
Could you read it to me?

79
00:07:14,032 --> 00:07:16,330
Is this what you want to do?

80
00:07:16,435 --> 00:07:20,337
I tried to read it a hundred different times.

81
00:07:21,306 --> 00:07:23,297
Mom, it's not exactly...

82
00:07:23,408 --> 00:07:26,809
It's just the sound of your voice, darling.

83
00:07:27,446 --> 00:07:28,640
Okay.

84
00:07:31,783 --> 00:07:34,752
It's dated April 4th, 1985.

85
00:07:35,887 --> 00:07:38,219
And it says New Orleans.

86
00:07:38,323 --> 00:07:41,053
"This is my last will and testament.

87
00:07:41,159 --> 00:07:45,357
"I don't have much to leave, few
possessions, no money, really.

88
00:07:45,764 --> 00:07:50,997
"I will go out of this world the same
way I came in, alone and with nothing.

89
00:07:51,670 --> 00:07:53,505
"All I have is my story,

90
00:07:53,638 --> 00:07:57,039
"and I'm writing it now while I still remember it.

91
00:07:57,843 --> 00:08:01,006
"My name is Benjamin. Benjamin Button."

92
00:08:01,379 --> 00:08:04,473
And I was born under unusual circumstances.

93
00:08:05,450 --> 00:08:07,680
The First World War had ended,

94
00:08:08,386 --> 00:08:12,254
and I've been told it was an
especially good night to be born.

95
00:08:13,892 --> 00:08:16,053
Thank God it's over!

96
00:08:16,161 --> 00:08:17,958
We won the war!

97
00:08:32,878 --> 00:08:34,675
The Great War is over!

98
00:08:46,958 --> 00:08:47,982
What are you doing here?

99
00:08:48,093 --> 00:08:49,390
Thomas,

100
00:08:50,629 --> 00:08:52,062
I'm afraid she's going to die.

101
00:08:52,163 --> 00:08:53,323
What?

102
00:08:54,499 --> 00:08:58,128
That's enough. All of you, get away from her.

103
00:09:01,339 --> 00:09:04,433
I came as quickly as I could. The
streets are filled with people.

104
00:09:04,543 --> 00:09:05,805
Thomas.

105
00:09:06,311 --> 00:09:08,905
Promise me he has a place.

106
00:09:11,316 --> 00:09:12,442
Yeah.

107
00:09:13,818 --> 00:09:15,809
She gave her life for me.

108
00:09:16,855 --> 00:09:19,824
And for that, I am forever grateful.

109
00:09:29,434 --> 00:09:30,833
Mr. Button.

110
00:09:46,151 --> 00:09:47,379
Thomas!

111
00:09:47,485 --> 00:09:48,713
Thomas.

112
00:09:50,722 --> 00:09:52,883
Thomas? Where are you going?

113
00:10:21,519 --> 00:10:23,851
Hey! What are you doing there?

114
00:10:25,090 --> 00:10:27,115
What do you have there?

115
00:11:24,783 --> 00:11:27,115
- Come on, Queenie.
- Now, Mr. Weathers!

116
00:11:27,218 --> 00:11:30,585
Come on, now, you know I ain't got
nothing but work to do around here.

117
00:11:30,689 --> 00:11:32,953
- Come on. Just take some time.
- Stop all this foolishness.

118
00:11:36,161 --> 00:11:37,924
The air is sweet.

119
00:11:42,367 --> 00:11:45,427
You look very handsome tonight, Miss Queenie.

120
00:11:46,771 --> 00:11:48,898
Handsome as I've ever seen.

121
00:11:50,341 --> 00:11:52,571
The brown matches your eyes.

122
00:11:52,677 --> 00:11:54,008
Oh, hush!

123
00:11:55,480 --> 00:11:59,610
Let's see here. You ain't no slouch yourself.

124
00:12:08,193 --> 00:12:09,990
Hambert's back in town.

125
00:12:10,095 --> 00:12:13,861
He came home legless, but he's home.

126
00:12:14,866 --> 00:12:17,494
I know you were sweet on him one time.

127
00:12:18,036 --> 00:12:19,901
Sweeter than I should have been.

128
00:12:20,004 --> 00:12:21,904
Miss Simone messed herself.

129
00:12:22,006 --> 00:12:23,234
Oh, sweet Jesus.

130
00:12:23,341 --> 00:12:25,866
She got to stop doing that or it's diapers for her.

131
00:12:25,977 --> 00:12:28,002
- I'll be right there, Miss Jameson!
- Now, Queenie, now come on.

132
00:12:28,113 --> 00:12:30,673
Okay, Queenie'll be right there.

133
00:12:30,782 --> 00:12:32,044
It's awful nice out here.

134
00:12:32,150 --> 00:12:35,347
Come on out back for a moment.
Take your mind off things.

135
00:12:35,453 --> 00:12:36,477
You're so bad.

136
00:12:36,588 --> 00:12:39,056
- What in God's name?
- What's this?

137
00:12:49,434 --> 00:12:51,664
Oh, the Lord done something here.

138
00:12:51,770 --> 00:12:55,262
Hope I didn't hurt it none stepping on it like that.

139
00:12:55,373 --> 00:12:56,897
We best leave that for the police.

140
00:12:57,008 --> 00:12:58,498
Poor baby.

141
00:12:59,344 --> 00:13:00,675
I'll go.

142
00:13:01,346 --> 00:13:05,009
It's for sure nobody wanted to keep it. Come on, baby.

143
00:13:07,685 --> 00:13:10,119
Queenie? Where are you, Queenie?

144
00:13:10,221 --> 00:13:12,155
Hold your water! You go deal with it.

145
00:13:12,257 --> 00:13:14,350
Okay. No, go, I'll be back.

146
00:13:15,226 --> 00:13:18,491
Queenie, Apple, she went and
messed herself all over again!

147
00:13:18,596 --> 00:13:20,461
Jane Childress, start her a bath!

148
00:13:20,565 --> 00:13:22,624
And mind your own business, Mrs. Duprey.

149
00:13:22,734 --> 00:13:24,531
You'll be messing yourself soon enough.

150
00:13:24,636 --> 00:13:26,194
Somebody stole my necklace.

151
00:13:26,304 --> 00:13:29,239
Okay. All right, Mrs. Hollister,
I'll be right with you, okay?

152
00:13:29,340 --> 00:13:31,535
Go on back upstairs, hear?

153
00:13:37,849 --> 00:13:40,374
You are as ugly as an old pot

154
00:13:40,485 --> 00:13:42,146
but you're still a child of God.

155
00:13:42,253 --> 00:13:44,619
Queenie, Apple, she won't take a bath without you!

156
00:13:44,722 --> 00:13:46,189
Mercy.

157
00:13:46,291 --> 00:13:48,259
I'll be right there!

158
00:13:51,296 --> 00:13:54,231
Okay. You just wait right here for me now, okay?

159
00:13:57,569 --> 00:14:02,199
My sister gave me those pearls.
I can't find them anywhere.

160
00:14:02,307 --> 00:14:06,141
- Somebody's been stealing my jewelry.
- They're right here, Mrs. Hollister. See?

161
00:14:06,244 --> 00:14:09,543
Right around your pretty white neck.
Now, come on. Hush all that noise.

162
00:14:09,647 --> 00:14:12,241
- Is Dr. Rose still here?
- I don't know.

163
00:14:15,053 --> 00:14:16,350
Your heart is strong.

164
00:14:16,454 --> 00:14:19,423
You just want to avoid any undue stimulation.

165
00:14:20,024 --> 00:14:23,118
I trust you ladies will help me out with that?

166
00:14:23,228 --> 00:14:26,356
I have something. Could you come downstairs?

167
00:14:30,068 --> 00:14:33,765
Never seen anything like it.
Nearly blind from cataracts.

168
00:14:33,872 --> 00:14:37,933
I'm not sure if he can hear. His
bones indicate severe arthritis.

169
00:14:38,776 --> 00:14:43,145
His skin has lost all elasticity,
and his hands and feet are ossified.

170
00:14:43,248 --> 00:14:47,844
He shows all the deterioration,
the infirmities, not of a newborn,

171
00:14:47,952 --> 00:14:50,580
but of a man well in his 80s on his way to the grave.

172
00:14:50,688 --> 00:14:51,677
He's dying?

173
00:14:51,789 --> 00:14:55,020
His body is failing him before his life's begun.

174
00:14:57,395 --> 00:14:58,828
Where'd he come from?

175
00:14:58,930 --> 00:15:03,299
My sister's child. From Lafayette.
She had an unfortunate adventure.

176
00:15:03,401 --> 00:15:07,303
The poor child, he got the worst of it. Come out white.

177
00:15:10,341 --> 00:15:14,937
There are places for unwanted
babies like these, Queenie.

178
00:15:15,580 --> 00:15:18,242
No room for another mouth to feed here.

179
00:15:18,349 --> 00:15:20,874
The Nolan Foundation, despite their good intentions,

180
00:15:20,985 --> 00:15:23,749
thinks this place is a large nuisance as it is.

181
00:15:23,855 --> 00:15:26,014
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

182
00:15:26,124 --> 00:15:30,686
Queenie, some creatures aren't meant to survive.

183
00:15:34,098 --> 00:15:37,829
No, this baby, he is a miracle. That's for certain.

184
00:15:37,936 --> 00:15:40,928
Just not the kind of miracle one hopes to see.

185
00:15:43,975 --> 00:15:46,466
Y'all listen. Y'all listen up here.

186
00:15:47,245 --> 00:15:48,269
We're gonna have us a visitor

187
00:15:48,379 --> 00:15:51,473
that's gonna be staying with us for a little while.

188
00:15:51,582 --> 00:15:55,279
My sister had a child and she
couldn't see right by it, so...

189
00:15:57,555 --> 00:15:59,284
He's known as...

190
00:16:02,560 --> 00:16:03,857
Benjamin.

191
00:16:04,529 --> 00:16:05,826
Benjamin.

192
00:16:06,731 --> 00:16:09,666
He's not a well child, so we're
gonna have to take good care of him.

193
00:16:09,767 --> 00:16:10,825
I had 10 children.

194
00:16:10,935 --> 00:16:14,268
There's not a baby I can't care for. Let me see him.

195
00:16:16,474 --> 00:16:20,103
God in Heaven. He looks just like my ex-husband.

196
00:16:20,945 --> 00:16:23,573
Look, he's prematurely old.

197
00:16:24,082 --> 00:16:27,609
Dr. Rose said he ain't got
much more time on this earth.

198
00:16:27,952 --> 00:16:29,078
Join the club.

199
00:16:34,192 --> 00:16:35,659
He's smiling!

200
00:16:42,433 --> 00:16:45,095
Hambert sends his remembrances to you.

201
00:16:54,912 --> 00:16:57,244
Are you right out of your mind?

202
00:16:58,549 --> 00:17:01,916
I know you ain't got all the parts
it takes to make one of your own,

203
00:17:02,020 --> 00:17:03,248
but this ain't yours to keep.

204
00:17:03,354 --> 00:17:05,618
It may not even be humankind.

205
00:17:14,766 --> 00:17:17,166
Mr. Weathers, come back here.

206
00:17:19,504 --> 00:17:20,732
Please.

207
00:17:37,088 --> 00:17:39,648
You never know what's coming for you.

208
00:17:49,667 --> 00:17:52,033
It seemed I had found a home.

209
00:17:55,206 --> 00:17:56,264
Is any of this true?

210
00:17:56,374 --> 00:17:59,741
You have such a lovely voice.

211
00:18:00,311 --> 00:18:04,975
Mom, it's an ancient streetcar token.

212
00:18:06,684 --> 00:18:09,812
That clock just kept going,

213
00:18:10,822 --> 00:18:15,020
year after year after year.

214
00:18:19,330 --> 00:18:21,230
But I didn't know I was a child.

215
00:18:21,332 --> 00:18:23,800
Same old crap every day.

216
00:18:24,702 --> 00:18:27,466
I thought I was like everyone else there.

217
00:18:28,473 --> 00:18:30,634
An old man in the twilight of his life.

218
00:18:30,741 --> 00:18:33,073
Could you make him stop that?

219
00:18:34,078 --> 00:18:37,138
Stop banging that fork. It's used
for eating, not for playing with.

220
00:18:37,248 --> 00:18:40,081
And use your napkin, please, Mr. Benjamin.

221
00:18:42,453 --> 00:18:43,715
Queenie!

222
00:18:55,800 --> 00:18:57,097
Hey, boy.

223
00:19:04,475 --> 00:19:06,773
Always had a healthy curiosity.

224
00:19:07,945 --> 00:19:11,403
What was up the street? Or around the next corner?

225
00:19:13,284 --> 00:19:14,581
Go get him!

226
00:19:14,685 --> 00:19:18,382
Benjamin! That is dangerous. Come back over here.

227
00:19:19,123 --> 00:19:20,852
Stay put, child.

228
00:19:23,227 --> 00:19:25,161
I loved her very much.

229
00:19:25,963 --> 00:19:27,590
She was my mother.

230
00:19:27,698 --> 00:19:28,858
Mama.

231
00:19:29,567 --> 00:19:30,693
Mama.

232
00:19:31,502 --> 00:19:35,268
Some days I feel different than the day before.

233
00:19:36,707 --> 00:19:40,734
Everybody feels different about
themselves, one way or another.

234
00:19:41,712 --> 00:19:44,010
But we're all going the same way.

235
00:19:45,383 --> 00:19:49,046
Just taking different roads to get there, that's all.

236
00:19:49,153 --> 00:19:51,621
You're on your own road, Benjamin.

237
00:19:54,392 --> 00:19:57,054
Mama? How much longer I got?

238
00:19:57,562 --> 00:20:00,861
Just be thankful for what you're given, hear?

239
00:20:00,965 --> 00:20:04,025
You're already here longer than you're supposed to.

240
00:20:06,938 --> 00:20:09,839
Some nights, I'd have to sleep alone.

241
00:20:18,549 --> 00:20:20,210
I didn't mind.

242
00:20:21,118 --> 00:20:23,848
I would listen to the house breathing.

243
00:20:25,056 --> 00:20:27,115
All those people sleeping.

244
00:20:28,593 --> 00:20:30,788
I felt safe.

245
00:20:51,649 --> 00:20:54,243
It was a place of great routine.

246
00:20:54,352 --> 00:20:57,253
Every morning at 5:30, no matter the weather,

247
00:20:57,355 --> 00:21:01,416
General Winslow, U.S. Army,
Retired, would raise the flag.

248
00:21:04,295 --> 00:21:08,254
Mrs. Sybil Wagner, once an opera singer of some note,

249
00:21:08,366 --> 00:21:10,994
well, she sang Wagner.

250
00:21:22,813 --> 00:21:24,246
All right, baby, come on.

251
00:21:24,348 --> 00:21:28,182
We got to put some life into these old sticks for you.

252
00:21:28,286 --> 00:21:32,586
Get you walking so you can help me
out around here. Come on now, hear?

253
00:21:33,691 --> 00:21:37,525
No matter the season, supper
was served promptly at 5:30.

254
00:21:37,628 --> 00:21:39,789
Molasses.

255
00:21:39,897 --> 00:21:41,125
Molasses.

256
00:21:42,366 --> 00:21:43,924
Molasses.

257
00:21:44,902 --> 00:21:47,427
I learned to read when I was five.

258
00:21:48,539 --> 00:21:51,940
My grandfather was a dresser for a famous actor.

259
00:21:52,043 --> 00:21:54,739
He brung home every play for me to read.

260
00:21:56,981 --> 00:22:00,712
"Kind keepers of my weak decaying age,

261
00:22:01,652 --> 00:22:05,247
"Let dying Mortimer here rest himself.

